And it's like, oh, that's next level compared to clinical trial reporting, right?

00:39:20.060 --> 00:39:24.939
Yeah, and we have certain people who kind of met.

00:39:24.939 --> 00:39:30.620
So for example, I'm leading one of the groups in the book club, and I have pretty experienced

00:39:30.699 --> 00:39:34.139
programmers in my team as well.

00:39:34.139 --> 00:39:43.100
And we're just, by reading the chapter, something comes up like data formats or how to deal

00:39:43.100 --> 00:39:46.379
with a big amount of data and stuff.

00:39:46.379 --> 00:39:52.219
And we just start sharing the packages, the workflows, and even certain people who have

00:39:52.219 --> 00:40:00.139
been working with R for a while, they might not use certain tools that people who maybe

00:40:00.139 --> 00:40:06.939
attended certain sessions heard about certain tools, then the sharing process becomes inevitable

00:40:06.939 --> 00:40:09.899
and leads to greater collaboration as well.

00:40:11.260 --> 00:40:17.820
I was just actually talking about that internally too with Rich who created the GT package.

00:40:17.820 --> 00:40:22.379
And he was starting to think about how he could use pins and hadn't thought too much

00:40:22.379 --> 00:40:23.340
about pins.

00:40:23.340 --> 00:40:27.179
So I was sharing some resources that I had seen and that we shared in the Hangout.

00:40:27.820 --> 00:40:33.419
And so it was cool just to see how you can speed up that process for somebody by helping

00:40:33.419 --> 00:40:35.340
share resources with them.

00:40:36.219 --> 00:40:38.219
Javier, I see you have your hand raised here.

00:40:41.899 --> 00:40:42.540
Thanks, Rachel.

00:40:43.340 --> 00:40:44.379
I'll lower my hand here.

00:40:45.419 --> 00:40:47.020
Natalia, great talk so far.

00:40:47.020 --> 00:40:47.979
This has been excellent.

00:40:48.699 --> 00:40:52.060
And I appreciate Mike chiming in also here and there.

00:40:52.699 --> 00:40:59.899
So we just recently started at our company these coffee chat series where we're paired

00:40:59.899 --> 00:41:05.820
with an individual in another group, like really not related at all.

00:41:06.780 --> 00:41:13.179
And I was recently sitting on a call with a leader and just in introducing ourselves,

00:41:13.179 --> 00:41:15.100
we started talking about R.

00:41:15.659 --> 00:41:23.260
And he told me very seriously, oh, yeah, no, that's interesting.

00:41:23.899 --> 00:41:31.020
We don't use R in our organization because it's really a statistical language.

00:41:31.020 --> 00:41:35.659
And that's all it can do versus Python that can do X, Y, and Z.

00:41:36.459 --> 00:41:38.540
And I was sort of taken aback.

00:41:38.540 --> 00:41:43.500
Like, oh, my God, how have you not heard about all these resources we have at the company

00:41:43.500 --> 00:41:51.340
for, you know, not just the positive professional products, but also like what R can do in 2023.

00:41:52.379 --> 00:42:00.219
And it dawned on me that, like, I don't, I still struggle with, like, finding these

00:42:00.219 --> 00:42:07.419
pockets of individuals or organizations in other parts of the company to educate them

00:42:07.419 --> 00:42:09.739
on, like, modern R usage.

00:42:09.739 --> 00:42:15.979
So it's kind of an open-ended question, but do you have any tips on, like, how to sort

00:42:15.979 --> 00:42:17.820
of spread the word to these types of people?

00:42:17.820 --> 00:42:23.899
Do you have maybe a landing page or something or a cordo page that your team has kind of

00:42:23.899 --> 00:42:27.260
opened up for the entire company or a confluence page?

00:42:27.260 --> 00:42:30.540
I just, I struggle with how to get the word out in that way.

00:42:31.979 --> 00:42:38.780
Yeah, we have, and this is a very good question because I'm asking myself that a lot, maybe

00:42:38.780 --> 00:42:39.340
once a month.

00:42:40.459 --> 00:42:42.699
So we have a lot of resources.

00:42:42.699 --> 00:42:47.260
We do have a confluence page, again, the Teams channel.

00:42:47.260 --> 00:42:53.580
We do have the associated, like, Microsoft Teams website that is associated with it where

00:42:53.580 --> 00:42:58.139
you can come, and there are tons of links that are cross-linked between the confluence

00:42:58.139 --> 00:43:01.340
and this website and then the Teams.

00:43:02.780 --> 00:43:08.459
For certain announcements, we're tagging the whole Teams channel so that people receive

00:43:08.459 --> 00:43:09.739
the notification.

00:43:09.739 --> 00:43:13.500
There are multiple channels within the whole channel.

00:43:13.500 --> 00:43:18.699
There are multiple extremes, questions and answers, general, R and pharma.

00:43:18.699 --> 00:43:20.939
So a lot of resources there.

00:43:23.500 --> 00:43:31.100
One thing that I think is a little bit hard is that sometimes you can work hard on actually

00:43:31.100 --> 00:43:33.260
creating those resources, and this is what we're doing.

00:43:33.260 --> 00:43:38.219
We created so much documentation since last year on various different topics.

00:43:38.219 --> 00:43:43.340
So the rule of thumb, if somebody's coming to us with a question and we answer this question,

00:43:43.340 --> 00:43:48.459
we write a confluence article about it, especially if it may be helpful for other colleagues

00:43:48.459 --> 00:43:50.060
within the organization.

00:43:50.060 --> 00:43:58.620
But I think the hard part is also marketing because the resources can be all there, available

00:43:58.620 --> 00:44:05.979
at any time, no passwords required, but people just kind of maybe choose to ignore it, not

00:44:05.979 --> 00:44:10.300
because they want to, it's because there's so many other things happening.

00:44:10.300 --> 00:44:11.979
They're working on the projects.

00:44:11.979 --> 00:44:13.419
The deadlines are approaching.

00:44:14.219 --> 00:44:22.620
I even had one colleague who asked me how to opt out of notifications.

00:44:22.620 --> 00:44:24.459
He's like, you're sending too many.

00:44:24.459 --> 00:44:25.580
How can I opt out?

00:44:26.139 --> 00:44:33.260
And it's kind of a situation where then the same person can later come and ask why he

00:44:33.340 --> 00:44:38.620
or she didn't see the announcement about the meeting that they were interested in.

00:44:39.580 --> 00:44:45.820
So I think there is a very thin balance of where you should notify people about upcoming

00:44:45.820 --> 00:44:52.860
events, but maybe don't overdo it because then it becomes a white noise and they just

00:44:52.860 --> 00:44:55.500
start ignoring all the notification and everything.

00:44:56.459 --> 00:45:03.580
What we chose to do is that during some of the events, like for example, in the community

00:45:03.580 --> 00:45:08.219
of practice events, we would make an announcement about hangouts and hangouts, we can make an

00:45:08.219 --> 00:45:11.020
announcement about book club or community of practice.

00:45:11.020 --> 00:45:17.260
So we're kind of cross-linking all the events and making announcements here and there because

00:45:17.260 --> 00:45:22.540
person can join one meeting, but then skip another one, but constantly reminding people

00:45:22.540 --> 00:45:26.540
about certain things that are going on are very helpful.

00:45:26.540 --> 00:45:36.219
And then we also discovered that maybe having easy access to certain resources, for example,

00:45:36.219 --> 00:45:43.020
if you have a Teams channel, make sure you pin certain messages or certain links in Teams

00:45:43.020 --> 00:45:49.260
so that it takes people one click, not two, but one click to get to the resources they

00:45:49.260 --> 00:45:49.899
need.

00:45:49.899 --> 00:45:57.260
And eventually, I think with a lot of training, this will become a pattern and people will

00:45:57.260 --> 00:46:04.699
start sharing the knowledge with other colleagues and they will start sharing those links with

00:46:04.699 --> 00:46:05.179
each other.

00:46:09.020 --> 00:46:09.520
Thank you.

00:46:10.620 --> 00:46:11.820
Yeah, thank you so much.

