and I'm not sure what I missed, but something I wanted to ask you is, if somebody in the

00:56:33.179 --> 00:56:38.620
group today was thinking about starting their own internal data science hangout, what's

00:56:38.620 --> 00:56:41.340
something that you've learned from that process?

00:56:42.300 --> 00:56:45.739
Yeah, so that's a good question.

00:56:48.060 --> 00:56:55.419
It was a little bit overwhelming to think about it and how to start it, but then one

00:56:55.419 --> 00:57:01.500
thing you would need is the list of people who, at least like 10 or 15 from the start,

00:57:02.060 --> 00:57:07.580
and then you would, what I would do, I just like give my example, I would send, I would

00:57:07.580 --> 00:57:09.020
identify the person.

00:57:09.260 --> 00:57:12.780
First, I created the calendar of events I would think would make sense.

00:57:13.580 --> 00:57:20.699
We do hangouts every other week, so I specifically put the dates I would invite people to, and

00:57:20.699 --> 00:57:26.780
then I will send them the invitation asking to be a part of hangout.

00:57:27.340 --> 00:57:34.219
I actually started hangouts with Mike, you know, and Douglas Robinson, he's also part

00:57:35.179 --> 00:57:42.699
of our core team who are moving initiative forward, so I thought it's a great start to

00:57:42.699 --> 00:57:47.020
start from the people who are actually like interested in also doing the hangouts.

00:57:47.580 --> 00:57:53.899
It will be first easy to hang out, especially maybe if you know colleagues or you work with

00:57:53.899 --> 00:57:58.620
certain colleagues that you already have a report established with, so do that and then

00:57:58.699 --> 00:58:05.979
invite people, and then I set up the Microsoft form that I would send out asking about, you

00:58:05.979 --> 00:58:12.620
know, regular information, occupation, bio, maybe certain questions they want me to ask,

00:58:12.620 --> 00:58:16.780
and then they would fill out the form, and I also ask them to provide their headshot.

00:58:16.780 --> 00:58:21.820
I think it makes the hangout invitation a little bit more colorful, and then what I

00:58:22.780 --> 00:58:31.179
still do now is that I schedule a 30-minute call with each guest like the week prior or something

00:58:31.179 --> 00:58:36.860
to go over any questions that person might have if they never attended the hangout or,

00:58:38.139 --> 00:58:43.979
you know, something that can come up, and then it actually helps me to know more about what

